# Cursor Agent Coding Rules (Next.js Frontend)

## 1. Code Consistency
- Always analyze existing frontend patterns before implementing new code.
- Match the current conventions exactly:
  - Component structure (functional components, hooks usage)
  - Naming (PascalCase for components, camelCase for variables/functions)
  - Styling approach (CSS Modules, Tailwind, styled-components, etc.)
  - Data fetching patterns (server actions, React Query, fetch, etc.)
- Do not introduce new patterns if an equivalent already exists.

---

## 2. Human-like Code Quality
- Write code as a senior frontend engineer would.
- Prefer clarity, composability, and predictability.
- Avoid over-engineering (no unnecessary hooks, abstractions, or memoization).
- Components should be easy to scan and reason about.

---

## 3. Minimal Changes Principle
- Avoid modifying unrelated components or files.
- Keep diffs small and focused.
- Do not refactor unless required for correctness.

---

## 4. Structural Discipline (Next.js)
- Follow the project’s routing system:
  - App Router (`app/`) or Pages Router (`pages/`) as already used.
- Respect boundaries:
  - Server Components vs Client Components (`"use client"`)
- Place logic correctly:
  - UI → components
  - State → hooks / state managers
  - Data fetching → server components / hooks / services
- Do not mix concerns (UI, state, API logic).

---

## 5. Component Design
- Prefer small, reusable, composable components.
- Extract logic into hooks when reused or complex.
- Avoid deeply nested JSX; break into subcomponents.
- Keep components focused on a single responsibility.

---

## 6. Naming & Semantics
- Prefer short, single-word names when they clearly convey intent:
  - Examples:
    - `header`, `footer`, `sidebar`
    - `hero`, `features`, `pricing`
    - `auth`, `dashboard`, `profile`
- Use nested structure instead of long names:
  - Prefer `sections/hero` over `homepage-hero-section`
- Avoid redundant prefixes/suffixes:
  - ❌ `user-component`, `header-section`, `button-component`
  - ✅ `user`, `header`, `button`
- Use multi-word names only when necessary for clarity:
  - `user-setting`, `payment-method`
- Keep naming consistent with existing project structure.
- Follow next.js naming practice


---

## 7. State Management
- Follow existing state strategy:
  - React state, Context, Zustand, Redux, etc.
- Do not introduce new state libraries without strong reason.
- Keep state minimal and colocated where possible.
- Avoid prop drilling if the project already uses a shared solution.

---

## 8. Data Fetching & API Usage
- Follow existing data-fetching approach:
  - Server Actions / fetch / React Query / SWR
- Do not mix multiple fetching paradigms arbitrarily.
- Handle loading, error, and empty states explicitly.
- Avoid redundant API calls.

---

## 9. Error Handling & UX States
- Always handle:
  - Loading states
  - Error states
  - Empty states
- Match existing UI/UX patterns for feedback (spinners, toasts, alerts).
- Do not silently fail.

---

## 10. Styling
- Follow the existing styling system strictly:
  - Tailwind / CSS Modules / styled-components / etc.
- Do not mix styling approaches.
- Reuse existing utility classes or design tokens.
- Keep class names clean and consistent.

---

## 11. Performance Awareness
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders:
  - Use memoization only when justified.
- Lazy load components if already practiced in the codebase.
- Keep bundle size in mind (avoid heavy dependencies).

---

## 12. Accessibility (a11y)
- Use semantic HTML elements.
- Ensure:
  - Proper labels for inputs
  - Keyboard accessibility
  - ARIA attributes when needed
- Follow existing accessibility patterns if defined.

---

## 13. Dependencies & Imports
- Reuse existing utilities, hooks, and components.
- Do not introduce new libraries unless necessary.
- Keep imports ordered and consistent with the project.

---

## 14. Comments & Documentation
- Prefer self-documenting code.
- Add comments only for non-obvious logic.
- Avoid redundant or obvious comments.

---

## 15. Formatting
- Follow existing formatting rules (Prettier, ESLint config).
- Do not reformat unrelated code.
- Maintain consistent spacing and structure.

---

## 16. Completeness
- Deliver production-ready code:
  - No TODOs or placeholders
  - No incomplete UI states
- Validate inputs and handle edge cases.
- Ensure components render safely under all conditions.

---

## 17. Testing Awareness
- Follow existing testing setup (Jest, RTL, etc.) if present.
- Ensure components are testable:
  - Avoid tightly coupled logic
  - Keep side effects controlled

---

## 18. Respect Existing Logic
- Do not break existing UI behavior.
- Assume current patterns are intentional.
- Only deviate when clearly necessary and justified.